			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">A CRT TV's electron beam sweeps across the width of the screen over 15,000 times per second and excites the phosphors at the front. The Super Scope operates in the same way as a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light_pen" class="postlink">light pen</a>: it has a photodiode that watches green and blue light emitted by the TV's phosphors and sends a signal to the receiver plugged into port 2 when the Scope detects light that matches the CRT's horizontal frequency. (Red phosphors turn on and off too slowly. This is why you see pinks and oranges in Scope games, never deep red.) The timing of this signal has a precision of a fraction of a tile, reportedly 2 pixels. With a pixel rate of 945/176 = 5.37 MHz, this means the timing is in units of 176*2*1000/945 = 372 ns.<br /><br />The NES Zapper operates in a similar manner. During the development of Zap Ruder, I discovered that its photosensor is accurate to only about 100 pixels across, or 176*100/945 = 18.6 us, but that's still enough to tell whether it's pointed up or down and at a bright or dark area. Games have to use a process of elimination, turning on only a few targets on each frame to determine which targets are being hit.<br /><br />LCDs can't modulate their pixels nearly that fast. In theory, it'd be possible to make a DLP compatible with CRT light pens, but I'm not aware of any commercial ones. An LCD light pen would need to read the position of faint dots on the screen, much like the Fly pentop computer or the LeapFrog Tag reader.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
